I:e                FASSical Studies 1990              Page 1


                       IIInnntttrrrooo ooofff III:iiivvv


CCChhhaaarrraaacccttteeerrrsss dddeeefffiiinnneeeddd fffooorrr ttthhhiiisss sssccceeennneee:

    1. <pro>   Professor . . . . . . . . . .  (Professor)

111-PPPRRROOOFFFEEESSSSSSOOORRR:   One  of  the great achievements of man is the
   ability to communicate ideas in many ways:  art,  poetry,
   and  language.   The  Renaissance  was a rebirth of these
   forms of expression, which  is  why,  I  suppose,  it  is
   called the Renaissance.

                          - fin -
A vital  focus  of  student  life  came  to  be  the  campus
newspaper,  giving  students  a  voice  through which to ex-
press their concerns.  This  tradition  reached  its  zenith
during  the  Renaissance when the beauty of language bloomed
in its fullest flower. There existed one campus blessed with
two  such  journals, the Imprint and the Gazette, two papers
both alike in infamy. We observe here the doings of the  Im-
print  office  on  a  hectic  Thurs- day before their Friday
deadline.

                          - fin -































